\[ C(n, m) = \frac{n!}{m! \cdot (n - m)!} \]

Given the constraints \( n \leq 20 \) and \( m \leq n \), we can safely compute factorials without worrying about integer overflow, as the maximum value of \( n! \) for \( n \leq 20 \) is \( 20! = 2,432,902,008,176,640,000 \), which fits within a 64-bit unsigned integer.

